column34: Belstar has proven to be widely adapted, and has performed particularly well in Florida in the winter. Heads are medium green and well-domed with a medium-size bead. Strong, stress-tolerant plants with good side-shoot production. For summer and fall harvest. USDA Certified Organic. Specs: Packet: 100 seeds Avg. 142,100 seeds/lb

column26: thinning to same plant density noted in transplanting recommendations.
column27: Space rows 18–36" apart, and transplant 4–6" apart within rows for ‘Melody', 12–18" apart for ‘Burgundy' and 'Sidekick', 12–24" apart for 'Bonarda', and 6–12" apart for all other varieties.
column34: Uniform, vigorous, dark green plants produce jumbo-size florets that resemble mini heads of broccoli, and have an excellent sweet broccoli flavor. This sprouting broccoli produces ample amounts of side shoots when plants are spaced 12–18" apart. For a single crop harvest, space plants 6–8" apart. Pinching not necessary. CULTURE: Prefers a well-drained, fertile soil high in organic matter with a pH of 6.0–7.5. Prefers a consistent supply of moisture throughout the growing season. Irrigate regularly for best results. TRANSPLANTING: Sow 2 seeds per cell in 72-cell plug flats, 3–4 seeds/in. in 20-row flats, or in outdoor beds ¼" deep. Seedlings should be ready to transplant in 3–4 weeks. If possible, keep soil temperature 75–85°F (24–29°C) until germination, then reduce air temperature to about 60°F (16°C). Ensure good air circulation and light. DIRECT SEEDING: Sow 2–3 seeds/ft., ½" deep, rows 18–36" apart, thinning to same plant density noted in transplanting recommendations. INSECT PESTS AND DISEASE: Prevent flea beetle damage by applying floating row cover at planting. Flea beetles can also be controlled with insecticides such as azadirachtin or pyrethrin. Cabbage worms can be controlled with Bacillus thuringiensis. Prevent disease with crop rotation and good sanitation. CROP MAINTENANCE: For some varieties, side-shoot production can be increased by pinching the initial head as soon as it forms. HARVEST: Before flower buds open, cut stems of central head and side shoots. Stems 4–8" in length can be bunched for sale or sold loose. Harvest side shoots every 2–3 days in warm weather and every 5–7 days in cool weather to encourage continued production.

Bronco has become a standard due to its wide adaptability and reliability. Heads average 3–5 lb. and have a short core and very good eating quality. Upright plant allows for optimal air circulation and less disease pressure. USDA Certified Organic. Disease Resistance: Fusarium Yellows (High) Specs: Packet: 50 seeds Avg. 75,900 seeds/lb

Compared to Haku, Bilko is slightly bigger at 12", darker green, and a couple of days later. Wide adaptability. Slow-bolting heads have a good, mild, sweet flavor. USDA Certified Organic. Disease Resistance: Club Root (High) Fusarium Yellows (High). Specs: Packet: 100 seeds; Avg. 135,400 seeds/lb

Compared to Touchstone Gold, germination and seedling vigor are a bit better, and interior color is a shade lighter. Otherwise, it is very similar, with strong tops and great flavor. Also keeps its color when cooked. Also available with NOP-compliant pelleting. USDA Certified Organic. Culture: First-rate crops grow quickly in light or loamy soils with a pH over 6.0; cool temperatures produce the best flesh color. Disease: Keep beets well-irrigated to prevent scab, which causes raised brown rough spots on mature roots. Internal breakdown or browning is most likely to occur in alkaline soils after prolonged hot, dry periods and is caused by a boron deficiency. Rotate crops to prevent Cercospora leaf spot.

Widely adapted and reliable. Smooth, rich red skin and excellent flavor. Attractive, fine taproot. Big healthy tops. Stores well through the winter in proper conditions. Also available with NOP-compliant pelleting. USDA Certified Organic. Specs: Packet: 350 seeds Avg. 51,300 seeds/lb

Adaptable and flavorful variety with great dormancy in storage. Firm, crunchy, and balanced sweet, carroty flavor. At 7–9", slightly longer and broader than Bolero allowing for higher yield potential. Slower to tip fill than Bolero. At full maturity, roots are straight and smooth. Aggressive tall tops can compete with weeds and combat foliar diseases such as Alternaria dauci . USDA Certified Organic. Specs: Packet: 750 seeds Avg. 350,000 seeds/lb

Medium-long 7–8" roots are uniform, thick, slightly tapered, and blunt. Excellent eating quality both fresh and after long-term storage, with juicy texture and sweet, complex flavor. A great choice for fall and winter harvest. Tops are vigorous, fast, and healthy which makes for better field-holding ability and easier mechanical harvesting. Heavy Nantes type. Also available with NOP-compliant pelleting. Disease Resistance: Alternaria Blight (High) Bacterial Blight (Intermediate) Cavity Spot (Intermediate) Cercospora Blight (Intermediate) Powdery Mildew (High) Specs: Packet: 750 seeds Avg. 250,400 seeds/lb

A specially designed blend based on two years of trial research to make your salad mix stand out from the crowd. Selected varieties yield darker reds and greens even under low-light conditions. Ruffled edges and unique leaf shapes provide loft, interesting texture, good shelf life, and fancy appearance. Includes green oakleaf, red oakleaf, green romaine, red romaine, lollo rossa, and red leaf lettuces. MT0-30. Varieties are subject to change depending upon availability. Specs: Packet: 1,000 seeds Avg. 26,440 seeds/oz

column20: Seeds germinate in soil temperatures from 40–100°F (5–38°C) with an optimum of 86°F (30°C)
column34: Nicely savoyed and glossy green or bronze leaves with stems of many colors including gold, pink, orange, red, and white with bright, pastel, and multicolored variations. The flavor is milder than ordinary chard, with each color a bit different. Direct seed or grow from transplant which allows separating out the individual colors. Consistent growth rate, leaf shape and texture, and strong bolt resistance across all colors makes this a superior mix. Suitable for production year-round, but somewhat less frost hardy than other chards. The late New Zealand amateur breeder John Eaton developed Bright Lights, and Johnny's selects and maintains the different color stocks and produces the seeds. AAS Winner. Decorticated (rubbed) seeds. Also available with NOP-compliant pelleting. Specs: Packet: 200 seeds Avg. 30,400 seeds/lb

A great combination of both mild and spicy ingredients. Includes red mustard, mizuna, tatsoi, kale, and arugula. NOTE: To increase the expression of red coloration, sow seed more sparsely. Varieties are subject to change depending upon availability. USDA Certified Organic. CULTURE: For cultural information, see the baby-leaf brassica greens culture. DAYS TO MATURITY: From date of direct seeding. DIRECT SEEDING: Sow ¼" deep at 3–5 seeds/inch, in rows at least 2" apart from early spring to midsummer. For a continuous supply sow about every 2 weeks. AVG. DIRECT SEEDING RATE: 1,000 seeds/16', 1 oz./200', 1 lb./3,200' at 60 seeds per foot. SUGGESTED SEEDERS: JP-1 with suggested Jang Rollers X-24 and F-24; Earthway Seeder; Six-Row Seeder; One-Row Pinpoint Seeder; Four-Row Pinpoint Seeder. SEEDS/OZ. (AVG.): 13,750. PACKET: 1,000 seeds, sows 16'.

Highly adaptable variety with great flavor and tender stalks. Tango performs well under less-than-ideal growing conditions such as heat or moisture stress. Can be winter grown in milder climates for cut-and-come-again stalks for bunching. Also available with NOP-compliant pelleting. USDA Certified Organic. Specs: Packet: 250 seeds Avg. 66,700 seeds/oz

column26: Thin to 1 1/2–2" apart for highest yields in fertile soil; thin to 3-4" apart for larger onions.
column34: Maragogi is a productive yellow short-day onion for the early/main season. Offers a great balance of earliness, yield, and exceptional uniformity. With intermediate resistance to Fusarium and pink root rot, Maragogi's healhy plants produce attractive jumbo-sized granex bulbs with a high percentage of single centers. For short storage (2–3 months) under ideal conditions. Disease Resistance: Fusarium Basal Rot (Intermediate) Pink Root (Intermediate) Specs: Packet: 250 seeds Avg. 87,100 seeds/lb

column18: organic, dwarf - no trellis required, container-friendly
organic, dwarf - no trellis required, high-yielding

column34: Smooth, deep red beefsteak sets fruit in heat when other tomatoes will not. Round, clean, 8–10 oz. lightly ribbed fruits for mature-green and vine-ripe markets. Improved plant health, production, and fruit quality over Grand Marshall. Strong TYLCV resistance for growers in the Deep South. Determinate. Disease Resistance: Fusarium Crown and Root Rot (High); Fusarium Wilt races 1–2 (High); Tomato Yellow Leaf Curl Virus (High); Verticillium Wilt (High). Culture: Medium-rich soil with pH 6.0–6.8 preferred; fertilize accurately. Tomatoes typically germinate in 5–7 days. Transplanting: sow 1/4" deep in 20-row flats with 20 seeds/row or in 200-cell trays with 1 seed/cell; keep mix at 75–85°F (24–29°C) with moderate moisture. At first true leaf, pot-up to 50-cell trays or 4" pots; grow at constant 60–70°F (16–21°C) until hardened off. Avoid exposing unprotected plants to consecutive nightly temperatures below 45°F (7°C). In rows 4–6' apart, space determinates 12–24". Plant deeply to encourage adventitious rooting. Trellising and pruning recommendations and harvest/storage guidance provided.

Similar to Juliet, but with even tastier, somewhat more plump, deep red "cocktail plum" fruits averaging 2 1/2 oz. Long clusters on a medium-vigorous vine. Indeterminate. USDA Certified Organic. Disease Resistance: Early Blight (Intermediate) Fusarium Wilt races 1 (High) Verticillium Wilt (High) Specs: Packet: 15 seeds Avg. 15,200 seeds/oz

Large smooth fruits are blocky to slightly elongated in shape. Medium-sized plants with an exceptional canopy to protect the fruits from sun scald. Performs well in California and the Pacific Northwest. Disease Resistance: Bacterial Leaf Spot races 1–3, 7–8 (High) Phytophthora Blight (Intermediate) Tobamovirus races 0 (High) Tomato Spotted Wilt Virus (Intermediate). Specs: Packet: 25 seeds; Avg. 60,300 seeds/lb.

Conical-shaped fruits are thin walled, avg. 4" long, and ripen to a bright red. Their flavor is sweet, mildly hot, and very good. Excellent for fresh use, stir fries, sautéing, and hot sauce. AAS Winner. Disease Resistance: Tobamovirus races 0 (High) Specs: Packet: 25 seeds Avg. 6,050 seeds/oz

The 2 and 3-lobed fruits are smooth, shiny, and very dark green. Similar in appearance to Baron, but fruits average slightly larger at 5–6" long x 3" wide. Plants are tall, vigorous, and have an excellent yield potential. Disease Resistance: Phytophthora Blight (Intermediate) Specs: Packet: 25 seeds Avg. 54,900 seeds/lb

A wonder in the kitchen: elongated shape and minimal seeds for quick cooking and rich flavor. Prolific yields of highly uniform, straight fruit; Avg. 8–10" long; green calyx. Suitable for open-field and greenhouse production; popular in Turkey and the Middle East. Parthenocarpic; spineless; USDA Certified Organic. Culture: fertile, well-drained soil, pH 6.2-6.8. Sow indoors 6-8 weeks before planting; sow 4 seeds/in., ¼" deep; maintain soil temperature at 80-90°F (27-32°C) until emergence and 70°F (21°C) thereafter (seed will not germinate in cool soil). After true leaves form, thin to 2-3" apart in flats or transplant into 2-3" pots. Harden off by reducing water and temperature to ~60°F (16°C) for about a week. Transplant outdoors late spring/early summer once weather is settled; space transplants 18" apart in rows or 18-24" between plants. Avoid over-fertility (excess N causes vegetative growth with poor fruit set). Crop maintenance: may be pruned and staked. Insect pests: use fabric row covers for flea beetles and Colorado potato beetles; inspect for CPB egg masses. Disease: practice lengthy rotation to avoid Verticillium wilt (4-5 year rotation for Solanaceae). Harvest by clipping stems; pick regularly to encourage production. Transplants: Avg. 800 plants/1,000 seeds. Seeds/oz.: 6,500–8,400 (avg. 7,300).

Though bred for the South, The General has also performed well in our Maine trials. Dark fruits are uniform, attractive, and average 8–8 1/2" long. Flavor is superior to most modern American slicing varieties. The gynoecious plants have a high yield potential. NOTE: This variety is gynoecious, which means it will not produce the male flowers required for pollination. Seeds of a pollenizer variety have been mixed into the seed packet at a rate of 10%. As such, it is necessary to plant all seeds in the packet to produce cucumber fruits. Also available treated. Disease Resistance: Cucumber Mosaic Virus (Intermediate) Powdery Mildew (Intermediate) Scab (High) Specs: Packet: 30 seeds Avg. 16,500 seeds/lb

This traditional variety is well known for its buttery flavor and firm texture. Big plants are late to begin bearing, but then yield consistently over a long picking period. Best picked small, 4-5" long; larger fruits will have a bumpy appearance. USDA Certified Organic. Culture: Fertile, well-drained soil with a pH of 5.8–6.8 is best. Plastic mulch and fabric row covers (AG-19 grade) can aide plant establishment and exclude insect pests during the seedling stage; row covers should be removed when plants begin to flower. Poor fruit development may indicate insufficient pollination. For highest quality fruit, succession plantings every 2-3 weeks may be needed. Plant spacing: Space plants 18-24" apart in rows 6' apart; wider spacing may allow for easier harvesting. Diseases: Common cucurbit diseases include powdery mildew, downy mildew, bacterial wilt, and phytophthora—avoid problems with adequate soil drainage, good air flow, insect pest control, and crop rotation. Insect pests: Cucumber beetles, squash bugs, and vine borers are common; protect young plants with floating row cover. Control notes: squash bug eggs may be crushed by hand; for vine borers, cut out vines and hill soil over the wound; keep field borders mowed and remove plant refuse in the fall; pyrethrin sprays may offer some control. Harvest fruit regularly 2-3 times a week once plants produce; for summer squash harvest at about 4-6"; handle with care to avoid scratching fruits. Harvest blossoms in mid to late morning when fully open, clipping flowers 1-2" below flower base; if a fruit crop is desired, harvest only male blossoms, leaving some to pollinate females. Storage: Keep fruit at 40-50°F (5-10°C), 95% relative humidity for up to 2 weeks. Days to maturity: from direct seeding (subtract about 14 days if transplanting). Seed specs: Packet: 25 seeds; Avg. 6,300 seeds/lb (details). Growing-info seed spec: SEEDS/LB: Yellow Summer: Avg. 5,500; PACKET: 25 seeds, sows 8'. AVG DIRECT SEEDING RATE: (at 3 seeds/ft., rows 6' apart) 250 seeds/83', 500 seeds/166', 1,000 seeds/333'.

Attractive, straight fruits are borne on a spineless open plant which makes harvesting easy. Multiple disease resistances keep the plants bearing over an extended period. Disease Resistance: Powdery Mildew (Intermediate) Watermelon Mosaic Virus (Intermediate) Zucchini Yellow Mosaic Virus (Intermediate) Specs: Packet: 25 seeds Avg. 3,000 seeds/lb

Open habit and few spines make it easy to harvest blemish-free fruit. Excellent disease resistance keeps the plant productive over a long season. Bright yellow fruits with solid green stems. Disease Resistance: Powdery Mildew (Intermediate) Watermelon Mosaic Virus (Intermediate) Zucchini Yellow Mosaic Virus (Intermediate) Specs: Packet: 25 seeds Avg. 4,500 seeds/lb

Mambo moves to the same beat as Cha Cha, but their dance is not the same. Mambo displays notable improvements: higher yields; more uniform fruit; gorgeous darker color; and longer storage. Classic blocky buttercup shape but with no significant 'button' on the blossom end. Can be marketed as a buttercup or a kabocha. Stays dark green in storage. Developed by Johnny's Breeding Team. Avg. weight: 3–4 lb. USDA Certified Organic. Culture: Fertile, well-drained soil with a pH of 6.0–6.8 is best; plastic mulch and fabric row covers can aid establishment and exclude insect pests during the seedling stage (remove covers when plants begin to flower). Transplanting: Sow 2-3 seeds per 2" container or plug flat about 3 weeks prior to transplanting; thin to 1 plant/container or cell and harden 4–7 days before transplanting. Direct seeding: Sow 2 seeds at appropriate spacing, 1/2-1" deep; thin to 1 plant per spacing interval after seedlings are established. Diseases: Common cucurbit diseases include powdery mildew, downy mildew, bacterial wilt, and Phytophthora; avoid problems with adequate soil drainage, good air flow, insect pest control, and crop rotation. Insect pests: Cucumber beetles, squash bugs, and vine borers; protect young plants with floating row cover. Harvest: Fruits typically ready about 50-55 days after fruit set; harvest before hard frosts. Cure: Sun cure 5-7 days or cure indoors at 80-85°F/27-29°C with good ventilation. Storage: Store at 50-60°F/10-15°C, 50-70% RH; green varieties keep up to 4–5 months, Winter Sweet up to 6 months.

Just right for single servings when halved. Worthy of marketing by name. Semibush plant. Bred by the late Dr. Brent Loy at UNH. AAS Winner. Avg. weight: 1–1 1/4 lb. Disease Resistance: Powdery Mildew (Intermediate) Specs: Packet: 30 seeds Avg. 4,100 seeds/lb

column26: Thin to 1 plant/container or cell with scissors.
column27: Bush to short-vine habits generally require 6' between-row spacing, while long-vine habits require 12' between-row spacing. In-row spacing depends on fruit size as well as vine length and is generally: small fruit/bush or short vine type: 18-24"; medium fruit and vine length: 24-36"; large fruit or long vine length: 36-48".
column34: We lovingly referred to Block Party as ‘Miracle' and ‘Saint Butternut' in our breeding nursery because it was just too good to be true. Both its yield and storage results were unbelievably high without compromising on flavor. We named it ‘Block Party' for its compact blocky shape—a great efficiency when packing CSA boxes. Its thick neck means less waste when preparing or processing and it has a good flesh to seed cavity ratio. A great advancement in our butternut assortment. Developed by Johnny's Breeding Team. Avg. 3 1/2–4 1/2 lb. USDA Certified Organic. Disease Resistance: Powdery Mildew (Intermediate) Specs: Packet: 30 seeds Avg. 5,500 seeds/lb

Saniara produces high yields without sacrificing great flavor and sweetness. Nice internal color. Widely adapted plants handled stress well in our Maine trials. Avg. 11–15 1/2 lb. Disease Resistance: Fusarium Wilt (Intermediate) Specs: Packet: 15 seeds Avg. 8,300 seeds/lb

A unique sweet potato with bright pink skin and deep-orange flesh. A clear favorite in Johnny's taste tests. Extra sweet. No need to add sugar when cooked. Very good yields of uniform, blunt-ended roots in a very concentrated set. Excellent storage potential when cured properly. An exclusive selection developed over 20+ years by organic grower John Mahon. Despite the name, this variety is a sweet potato, not a yam. Plant Patent #20,666. USDA Certified Organic. SCIENTIFIC NAME: Ipomoea batatas. CULTURE: Sweet potatoes grow best in well-drained, sandy loam soil with a pH of about 6.5. You will receive bare-root slips. The slips may be dry, wilted, pale or brown in color when they arrive—this is normal. Slips may or may not have visible roots. A lack of visible roots does not negatively impact viability or yield. If planting must be delayed, wrap the root end of the slips in moist paper towels, keeping the leaves and stems dry. Place upright and keep at room temp., out of direct sunlight and wind. Plant out as soon as danger of frost has passed, and soil temp. is at least 60°F (16°C). In cold regions, black plastic mulch may help to warm the soil and is recommended. Plant slips 3-4" deep in raised beds 10-18" apart in rows 36-60" apart. Keep well-irrigated until plants are established. INSECT PESTS: Sweet potatoes are usually free from major insect infestations, but problems may arise from flea beetles, Japanese beetles, wireworms, and sweet potato weevils (in Southern US). DISEASE: Avoid diseases such as scurf with crop rotation and by removing all plant debris after harvest. HARVEST: Dig roots in fall before hard frost and before soil temps. drop to 50°F (10°C). If plants get frosted, harvest as soon as possible—frost damage will travel from the plants down into the roots, and affect storage quality. STORAGE: Brush soil from roots and cure in a warm 85°F (29°C), dark, humid (85% RH) and well-ventilated place for 4-7 days to toughen skin. Store at 60° (16°C), in a dark, humid place and avoid unnecessary handling.
